==English==
===Etymology===
:from the Late Latin ''verbalis'', belonging to a [[word]].

===Adjective===
'''verbal'''
#of, or relating to [[word]]s
#concerned with the words, rather than the [[substance]] of a [[text]]
#consisting of words only
#[[spoken]], as opposed to [[written]]; [[oral]].
#(''grammar'') derived from, or having the nature of a [[verb]]
#((''grammar'') used to form a verb

===Noun===
'''verbal'''
#(''grammar'') a verb form which does not function as a [[predicate]], or a word derived from a verb. In English, [[infinitive]]s, [[participle]]s and [[gerund]]s are verbals.
#a verbal [[statement]], especially a [[damaging]] [[admission]], alleged to have been made by a [[suspect]], and given in [[evidence]] at a [[trial]]

===Transitive verb===
'''to verbal'''
#To [[attribute]] a damaging statement to a suspect
#To [[fabricate]] a [[confession]]

